question: based Health Risk Assessment (HRA) and Interventions
answer:
To initiate the annual survey cycle, we send an email, or provide customers with email content, including simple access instructions to take the HRA. The HRA is administered online and is iOS- and Android-mobile compatible. If an individual is unable to access the survey online, it can be provided In hardcopy. We can also add questions and content as necessary and in future survey cycles. We have included a paper sample of our HRA with this proposal.

 NCQA Accredited 
 Our HRA was developed and received NCQA accreditation through our R&D partner Pro-Change Behavior Systems. The HRA is available online, in English and Spanish. A print-based version of the assessment is available, if needed. Personal feedback can be viewed on-screen or through a printed report. Insert NCQA logo here.

Validated Readiness to Change Assessment 
Unlike other health risk assessments, ours uses validated questions to assess readiness to change leading health risks and provides immediate feedback on the most important behavior change strategies based on empirically derived decision rules.

Evidence-based Personal Feedback Report 
Our personal feedback report provides evidence-based, stage-matched feedback about the single most important strategy individuals can use to make progress on that specific behavior.
Each time a user completes the survey, their feedback is updated to reflect change since the previous assessment. The report suggests online and community resources through which participants can learn more. Our assessment provides an overall Personal Health Report participants can share with their health care provider.

HRA Features
 In addition to health risks such as smoking, unhealthy eating, sedentary behavior, depression, and ineffective stress management, our evidence-based Survey also assesses:
• Current health conditions
• Adherence to United States Preventive Services Task Force recommendations for age and gender appropriate screenings and immunizations
• Productivity and well-being

question: process do you use to track patient satisfaction with your provider network?
answer:
Patient satisfaction falls under HMC's Quality Management program. Under our Patient Satisfaction policy and procedure, it is HMC’s policy to have a clear understanding of client satisfaction with programs, services and personnel, and to implement changes designed to increase satisfaction when appropriate. Below is a summary of the procedure we follow:
1) Account Management Reports
a) Bi-annual Account Management Report
i) Twice per year, Account Managers complete a report for each of their clients that includes satisfaction
ratings as well as narrative regarding particular barriers and successes.
ii) The Account Management reports are sent to the Vice President of Quality Management.
b) Weekly Account Management Reports
i) On a weekly basis, the Account Managers prepare a report on client activity.
ii) The Vice President of Quality Management is included in the distribution list for these weekly reports.
2) Reporting to the Quality Management Committee (QMC)
a) The Director of Quality Management receives the information noted above and produces a bi-annual summary
that is documented on the QMC Performance Monitoring report.
b) The summary report is presented to the QMC by the Vice President of Quality Management.
c) Based on the review and recommendations of the QMC:
i) Corrective Action Plans (CAP) will be initiated when needed to address areas of concern.
ii) If indicated, the application of a formal quality improvement project (QIP) will be applied.

question: do you avoid duplicate payments of the same claim? If duplicate payments or overpayments are made, what are your procedures for recovery of the overpayments or duplicate payments?
answer:
Our system is fully capable of identifying duplicate claims during claims processing and deny duplicate claims. The logic also checks for duplicates within the same claim to minimize the possibility of coding errors. 

Today, most of our clients are responsible for the actual claim payments, while we reprice the claim. For these clients, if an overpayment is confirmed, a Claims Resolution Examiner initiates communication between the provider and our customers for overpayment resolution. Our system is fully capable of overpayment recovery by placing a withhold against the providers next reimbursement check. This functionality is used for the clients that HMC HealthWorks is responsible for actual claims payment.

question: how your staff introduce themselves to patients for the first time (e.g., phone call, letter)?
answer:
Once a participant is identified by HMC HealthWorks for outreach, the initial method of outreach is by letter from HMC HealthWorks introducing the program.  For participants who are identified as moderate or high risk, a telephone outreach occurs following the letter. 
While participants are encouraged to call HMC HealthWorks to participant in the DM program; in most cases HMC HealthWorks' Enrollment Specialists make the initial phone call to enroll participants into the program.  Below is an outline of the enrollment call that our Enrollment Specialist (ES) would have upon reaching a participant:
1)   Introduce themselves, including full name and title.
2)   Welcome the participant and share the name of the program and where you are calling from (HMC HealthWorks).
• Provide participant with an explanation of how/why they are eligible for program participation. Include client specific incentive or disincentive information if applicable.  
• Provide verbal program overview. 
• Upon request, email or mail document to participant.
3)   Provide reason for the call including length of call and expectations. 
Include the following:
• The objective of the program is to support individuals in making healthy lifestyle changes.
• Through active participation in the program, participants can improve health outcomes.
• There is no cost to participate.
• PHI (personal health information) is kept according to HIPAA standards.
• The program is confidential.  Individual health information is not shared with the union or employer. This information is only available to the fund or third-party administrator (TPA) who has access to consumer health information in order to receive and pay claims for services rendered.
• Confidentiality is extended to the HMC HealthWorks' team of coaches including Nurse Health Advocates, wellness coaches, psychologists, psychiatrist, and the medical director. Consultation within the team occurs as situations outside the realm of expertise of the coach arise.
• Confidentiality is limited if there is mention of harm to self, others or abuse. 
• Coaching calls are periodically randomly monitored or recorded for quality purposes and training.
• Participants have the right to discontinue, change coaches, or register a complaint at any time by calling HMC HealthWorks' toll free number (provide participant with the client specific toll free number) .
• Details of participant rights and responsibilities can be emailed or mailed if requested by participant.
• Ask participant if there are any questions before moving forward with the session.
4)   Begin or continue with assessment, development/implementation of care plan goals and interventions.
5)   Answer questions the participant may have. 
6)   Provide reference information related to topic discussed during the call
7)   Schedule next call

question: would you say to a client whose health claims costs increased instead of decreased during the period of time that you were providing DM services?
answer: There are many reasons why a participant’s health claims costs could increase during a DM program, including appropriate use of pharmacy to maintain a chronic condition, spending in the near term to avoid acute events over the long term, as well as unavoidable health events unrelated to managing the chronic condition. It is important to understand the drivers for the cost increase to determine if the program is being effective in managing the long-term health of a participant and their chronic conditions, driving a cost savings over the life of the participant vs. short-term spending to stabilize a condition. The standardized reports are designed to track the effectiveness of the programs and progress each participant is making. Additionally, ad hoc reports can assist to evaluate health spend.

question: how your staff influence the targeted participants to modify their behavior.
answer: HMC HealthWorks uses the Transtheoretical Model (Prochaska). When our Nurse Health Advocates and/or Wellness Coaches work with participants, they engage in the process of assessing the readiness to change.  We chose this model for its integrative theory of therapy that assesses an individual's readiness to act on a new healthier behavior, as well as develop strategies and/or processes of change to guide the individual.

question: do you define "engagement"? Please be specific.
answer:
Engagement is defined as participants receiving coaching from a Nurse Care Manager. Also, below, is a further explanation of a participant status:
<IMAGE006.png>Targeted Population: Identified individuals who have one or more of the conditions covered by the program and are stratified as moderate or high risk.
Participant: Targeted individuals who agree to enroll and participate in the program.
Active: Participants who have agreed to engage in coaching and their first session is scheduled but has not yet been completed.
Engaged: Participants receiving Nurse Health Advocate coaching.
Declined to Continue: Participants who were engaged but decided to no longer continue with the program.
Well Managed: Participants who are determined by a Nurse Health Advocate to have successfully completed the program based on the demonstrated active and successful management of their condition.
All well-managed individuals are monitored and evaluated at least every 6 months. If they remain in a medium to high risk status, HMC HealthWorks will outreach to them again to engage in further coaching.
